<ns1227:section xmlns:ns1227="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="resources.information.platforms.linux.commands.hwclock">

  <ns1228:title xmlns:ns1228="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Setting the hardware clock</ns1228:title>
  <ns1229:para xmlns:ns1229="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    You can set the hardware clock in a similar way to setting the system date/time. The
    system clock is initialized by the hardware clock at boot time.
      <ns1230:cmdsynopsis xmlns:ns1230="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns1231:command xmlns:ns1231="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
hwclock --set --date "20030903 09:55:00"
      </ns1231:command></ns1230:cmdsynopsis>
  </ns1229:para>
  <ns1232:para xmlns:ns1232="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    Alternatively you may want to se the hardware clock equal to the system clock. This can be
    done via
    <ns1233:cmdsynopsis xmlns:ns1233="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns1234:command xmlns:ns1234="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
hwclock --systohc      
    </ns1234:command></ns1233:cmdsynopsis>
  </ns1232:para>
  
